Conclusions on 9-means clustering

The results are quite satisfactory, since in almost all the clusters there is one dominant region: the algorithm captured quite well the differences between regions. However, some areas such as Calabria and Apulia-South are prevalent in two clusters: one possible explanation for this is the high number of observations for these areas (especially for Apulia-South), which could lead to different features between products (-> high variability) and store products from the same region in different clusters. On the opposite side of the problem, regions with less observations (such as Sicily) does not identify precisely to one cluster, but their products belong to different groups together with observations from other regions.

Exercise 2

The result of the clustering will depend on three steps: the choice of the initial centroids, the computation of the new centroids at every step, and the minimization of the objective function.

Initial centroids

The choice of the initial centroids is randomic, so they will be k random observations which correspond to k observations from the original dataset multiplied by the quantity q.

Newly obtained Centroids

Step by step, the new centroids are computed as:

\(m_k=\frac{1}{n_k} \sum{x_i*q}= \frac{q}{n_k} \sum{x_i}\)

For this reason, the k final centroids of the clusters will be the same obtained with D, multiplied by the constant q.

Minimization of the euclidean distance

This step is performed using the tranformed observations \(x_i*q\) and the centroids:

\(\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^{n}{(q*x_i-q*m_{c(i)})}^2}=\sqrt{q^2\sum_{i=1}^{n}{(x_i-m_{c(i)})}^2}=q*\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^{n}{(x_i-m_{c(i)})}^2}\)

The euclidean distance computed in the transformed dataset is equal to the one computed in the original dataset, multiplied by a constant q. This constant doesnt affect the minimization, so at every step the algorithm minimizes the euclidean distance as it would have done in the original dataset.

Conclusions

The resulting clusters dont change if we multiply each variable for a constant q. The only change is a translation of the centroids in the p-dimensional space, where p is the number of the variables.

Exercise 4

The k-means++ procedure

The k-means++ procedure is an expansion of the standard k-means. The goal is to avoid the fact that sometimes the standard procedures generate a non-optimal clustering. This means that the approximations found by algorithms such as Lloyds could generate a too bad (=too high) value of the objective function, with respect to the optimal clustering. This problem is overcome by a method that initializes the centroids before starting the standard k-means. The algorithm is the following:

  1. Choose one centroid at random among the data points
  2. For each point x in the dataset, compute D(x), the distance between x and the farthest centroid
  3. Assign to each data point a weighted probability, proportional to \(D(x)^2\) and choose the next centroid according to such probability distribution.
  4. Repeat step 2 and 3 until k centroids have been chosen
  5. Run the standard k-means clustering

K-means with 1 initialization, K-means with 100 initializations and K-means++

library(pracma)
## Warning: il pacchetto 'pracma'  stato creato con R versione 4.2.3
kmpp <- function(X, k) {
        n <- nrow(X)
        C <- numeric(k)
        C[1] <- sample(1:n, 1)
        for (i in 2:k) {
          dm <- distmat(X, X[C, ])
          pr <- apply(dm, 1, min); pr[C] <- 0
          C[i] <- sample(1:n, 1, prob = pr)
        }
        
        kmeans(X, X[C, ])
}

geyser <- read.csv("geyser.dat", sep = " ")

plot(geyser, main = "Geyser Data")

geyser <- as.matrix(geyser)
set.seed(1111)
kmeanspp <- kmpp(geyser, k=3)
set.seed(1234)
kmeans1 <- kmeans(geyser, 3, nstart = 1)
set.seed(2345)
kmeans100 <- kmeans(geyser, 3, nstart = 100)
kmeans1$tot.withinss
## [1] 6388.563
kmeans100$tot.withinss
## [1] 6284.214
kmeanspp$tot.withinss
## [1] 6284.214

The within-sum of squares is greater for the k-means with 1 initialisation, while the within SS of the k-means++ coincides with the one for the k-means with 100 initializations. This makes sense because the k-means++ improves the value of the objective function through a smarter choice of the initial centroids, as does the randomization.

library(fpc)
plot(geyser,col=kmeanspp$cluster,pch=clusym[kmeanspp$cluster], main = "Geyser data: kmeans++ procedure")
